{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Heating Control System Analysis",
    "objective": "Synthesize the function and operating principles of electronic components within a practical heating control system.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a modern heating and boiler control system, electronic components are integrated to manage power, sense environmental conditions, and provide user feedback. The system must take the 230V AC mains supply and convert it to a stable DC voltage to power the internal logic. It then uses specialized sensors to monitor the water temperature and provides visual indicators to the user to show the system status.",
      "Understanding how these components interact is the key to effective fault-finding. If the display is dead, you look at the power conversion; if the boiler won't fire despite being cold, you look at the sensing components; if the boiler runs but the light is off, you check the indicator components."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are inspecting a boiler control panel. Identify the specific electronic components responsible for the following three tasks: 1) Converting the incoming 230V AC mains into the DC required by the control board; 2) Sensing the temperature of the water in the pipework; 3) Providing a visual 'Heating Active' light on the panel. Finally, explain the basic operating principle of the component used for temperature sensing.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "1) Rectifier (converts AC to DC)",
      "2) Thermistor (senses temperature)",
      "3) LED (visual indication)",
      "Operating Principle: A thermistor is a resistor whose resistance changes significantly in response to changes in temperature, allowing the control board to monitor heat levels."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about the 'one-way' nature of diodes in a power supply, the specific type of diode that glows, and the component whose very name suggests 'thermal' and 'resistor'."
  }
}

